### Decided
- Confirmed that the `ling05/06/07` numbering was correct and should not be reset per extraction run, because Ling subagent run IDs use a daemon-lifetime shared counter and earlier activity had already consumed `ling01`-`ling04`.
- Decided to move the app-skill dashboard hint text out of hardcoded Rust and into the TOML prompt store, matching the rest of the system-prompt architecture.
- Confirmed that `PageUpdate` is a real skill tool delivered alongside other tools, and that under native tool calling its schema is sent via the API `tools` parameter rather than embedded in the visible system prompt.
- Decided that system-prompt export should include native tool schemas in addition to the prompt text so debugging reflects the full model-facing context.

### Learned
- Historic session messages are delivered to the UI over the control channel via fetch-over-RPC, while live per-session streaming events use the `sess-{id}` session channel; the UI merges persisted history with streamed updates client-side.
- Session chat data stored in `messages.jsonl`, workspace-state responses, and page-state pushes do not contain the assembled system prompt or tool schemas; the prompt is rebuilt on demand from agent spec, active skill, memory, tool registry, permission context, and project instructions.
- The system prompt can change after session creation because it depends on mutable inputs such as memory files, active skill content, working directory/project context, permission mode, allowed tools, and plan mode.
- In native-tools mode, exported system prompts do not visibly include tool schemas unless the export endpoint adds them explicitly; otherwise tools like `PageUpdate` are still available to the model through the API-level `tools` payload.
- The memory skill prompt export the user reviewed correctly included both the global Ling instruction block and the active memory skill body, with `$SKILL_DIR` resolved to an absolute path.

